  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Pleased with my Treatment and A&amp;amp;amp;Ee a short headline summary&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Adrian&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I was transferred to A&amp;amp;amp;E via ambulance with a suspected heart attack. This was confirmed and I was treated in the department. After a few more diagnostic tests, I  waited most of the day on a trolley for a free bed in the CCU, eventually being moved in the early evening. The following morning I saw the consultant and his team were I was appraised of my situation and what the next steps would be. The care team decided to keep me in over the weekend and prioritised me  for transfer to Blackpool the following week for an angiogram. The A&amp;amp;amp;E was extremely busy and there was high demand for CCU beds, so my stay involved some periods of waiting. I have nothing but praise and thanks for the staff who provided my care. I felt all the staff had my ‘best interests at heart’ and I found the CCU staff very caring and approachable. Understandably I had a lot of questions, at a traumatic time for me and they always tried to give me the information. You read a lot in the media about the ‘stresses and strains’ on the NHS and at times, perhaps I saw it manifest itself here but I  wouldn’t have wanted to be anywhere else.  I am now well into my recovery, so Thank You, Royal Preston (This was my first inpatient stay).&lt;/CommentText&gt;
